===History===
Vacutainer technology was developed in 1947 by Joseph Kleiner,<ref name=Rosenfeld_2000>{{cite journal | author = Rosenfeld L | title = A golden age of clinical chemistry: 1948–1960 | journal = Clin Chem | volume = 46 | issue = 10 | pages = 1705–14 | year = 2000 | pmid = 11017957 | url = http://www.clinchem.org/cgi/content/full/46/10/1705 | access-date = 2015-10-04 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20110607111110/http://www.clinchem.org/cgi/content/full/46/10/1705 | archive-date = 2011-06-07 | dead-url = yes }}</ref> and is currently marketed by [[Becton_Dickinson|Becton Dickinson]] (B-D).<ref name=BD_guide>{{cite web | title = BD Vacutainer Venous Blood Collection – Tube Guide | url = http://www.bd.com/vacutainer/pdfs/plus_plastic_tubes_wallchart_tubeguide_VS5229.pdf | accessdate = 2007-05-30 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20141113233447/http://www.bd.com/vacutainer/pdfs/plus_plastic_tubes_wallchart_tubeguide_VS5229.pdf | archive-date = 2014-11-13 | dead-url = yes }}</ref>

The plastic tube version, known as Vacutainer PLUS, was developed at B-D in the early 1990s by E. Vogler, D. Montgomery and G. Harper amongst others of the Surface Science Group as US patents 5344611, 5326535, 5320812, 5257633 and 5246666.<ref name="US Patent Trademark Office">{{cite web|url=http://patft.uspto.gov/netahtml/PTO/srchnum.htm|title=US Patent Office Patent number search|access-date=2019-05-02|archive-date=2019-04-28|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190428053810/http://patft.uspto.gov/netahtml/PTO/srchnum.htm|dead-url=no}}</ref>

Vacutainers are widely used in [[phlebotomy|phlebotomy]] in developed countries due to safety and ease of use. Vacutainers have the advantage of being prepared with additives, allowing easy multi-tube draws, and having a lower chance of hemolysis.<ref>{{Cite journal | doi=10.1177/000456327501200136| pmid=15637911|title = An Appraisal of the "Vacutainer" System for Blood Collection| journal=Annals of Clinical Biochemistry: An International Journal of Biochemistry and Laboratory Medicine| volume=12| issue=1–6| pages=151–55|year = 1975|last1 = Ames|first1 = A.C.| last2=Bamford| first2=E.}}</ref> In developing countries, it is still common to draw blood using a syringe or syringes.
